Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgzwrLtbuwXeqDPaGgl4AaABAg,,@frankethomas1248,"Casablanca came out in 1942, which means that much of it was probably shot in 1941. Remember that America entered World War 2 in December of 1941, following the Japanese bombing of Pearl Harbor. And D-day was still  2.5 years away. So at the time this movie was made, and subsequently screened for various audiences, nobody knew how the war would end, or who would win. Under such dark & doleful conditions they made what is arguably the best movie ever. I enjoyed your reaction, ma'am; thank you for sharing this with us!",2026-05-07T03:32:54Z,2026-05-07T03:33:11Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-12T02:01:38.841767
Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,Ugwrt9k7EdvhUfiXaBV4AaABAg,,@jrepka01,"It's a great story of love and sacrifice. But it's really a story meant to convince the people of the US that entering the war was the right thing to do. The war had been going on in Europe for more than two years while America held back, not entering until Pearl Harbor was attacked in December 1941. 

When we are introduced to Rick in the beginning he is signing a document that is dated December 2 1941, just a few days before the Japanese attack, so the entire film takes place before the US committed to the war. At one point Rick says ""I'll bet they're asleep in New York. I'll bet they're asleep all over America” suggesting that Americans remain blissfully unconcerned about the fate of the rest of the world.

The movie was shot in early 1942, after the US had entered the war, and released at the end of that year. It was a great propaganda film, with the story of romance and betrayal playing an equal role to the story of courage and resistance to the fascist occupation. Many of the European actors in the film were only recent arrivals from occupied Europe, some with stories not too dissimilar to the stories in the movie itself. The La Marseillaise scene was particularly potent as none of the participants were ""acting"" while it was being filmed.",2026-05-07T02:00:11Z,2026-05-07T02:00:11Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-12T02:01:38.841774
Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgwLixDmn0N3eAtrbyh4AaABAg,,@Shadowace724,One of my all time favorite movies. Bogart is always cool and Ingrid Bergman is a radiant angel in this film. This is my first watch of reacting to a film. I think you have a heartfelt reaction to this film and I look forward to more of your reactions.,2026-05-07T01:09:33Z,2026-05-07T01:09:33Z,0,False,1.0,2026-05-12T02:01:38.841780
Casablanca,t2jBSAWCg5s,UgwL-u1oUYsN56t-qZ94AaABAg,,@timokaurala6657,"This is one of those rare movies that seem to get better every time you watch it. So many details in the lighting and camera work, how tight the plot is, yet how smoothly it seems to unfold, how everything seems to slot in perfectly as it wraps up. You'll watch this years from now and have a whole new appreciation for this beautifully made little movie.
Btw, the actors singing and being emotional in the national anthem scene were in real life refugees from France.  The tears you see in their faces and the emotional way they sang the French national anthem were real.",2026-05-07T00:41:20Z,2026-05-07T00:41:20Z,2,False,0.0,2026-05-12T02:01:38.841786
