Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugzw0hdsOOdS-EeaQdx4AaABAg.AD7aowz4S8bAECggtk3ww-,Ugzw0hdsOOdS-EeaQdx4AaABAg,@tkozikow,"Did you do a day trip to Essaouira or spend a couple of days there? We have four days in Marrakech next month and our riad highly recommends going there and we are trying to decide if it is worth the trip. From what I have been reading I think we want to go, but appreciate your thoughts.",2025-02-06T15:59:19Z,2025-02-06T15:59:19Z,1,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.049177
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugzw0hdsOOdS-EeaQdx4AaABAg.AD7aowz4S8bAIoklAX7TpL,Ugzw0hdsOOdS-EeaQdx4AaABAg,@Kaedehara_egiap,"​@tkozikow hey there! So my best friend and I are heading to Marrakesh for my 30th birthday in July, and I was wondering if you wouldn't mind sharing a bit about your experience and places to go when we're there. We don't mind taking a day trip out of Marrakesh, so anything you can provide would be great!",2025-06-01T06:10:49Z,2025-06-01T06:10:49Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.049184
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugzw0hdsOOdS-EeaQdx4AaABAg.AD7aowz4S8bAIzvTvW8LSe,Ugzw0hdsOOdS-EeaQdx4AaABAg,@tkozikow,"​@Kaedehara_egiap we booked our excursions directly through our riad, and the highlight was a day trip to the Ourika Valley. We had a private driver who arranged for a guide in Setti Fadma to accompany us on a waterfall hike.   There are plenty of small bus/group tours, but I would highly recommend spending the extra money... It was around $175, including the tip, for two people. We stopped at a couple of Berber villages along the way and purchased some pottery and a rug for a fraction of the cost it would be in Marrakech. The guide was around $40 and well worth the money. If you decide to do this, be sure to have decent shoes that are OK for light hiking.

I suggest hiring a guide to explore the souks and key areas inside the medina. You might encounter some sales pitches along the way, but it was an interesting five hours and provided us with ideas for what to explore on our own. You can easily book either of these through a service like Viator, but if you're staying at a decent riad, they should be able to coordinate this for you.

Definitely explore the alleyways and small streets in the medina for the best food and a glimpse of the culture. Marakech is very tourist-friendly, with something like 80% of its revenue based on this, and we never felt unsafe.",2025-06-05T14:16:05Z,2025-06-05T14:16:05Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.049189
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg.ACdy-O7b-QmACdyirKRdIP,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Thanks for watching! We have had good success with Airbnb experiences (we aren't affiliated in any way and make no money by recommending them). Our guide was a little bit corny, but he gave us good insights and overall was a great guide. Here's a link to the experience—Colourful Tour of Marrakesh: https://www.airbnb.com/experiences/604421 —Judy",2024-12-29T22:32:49Z,2024-12-29T22:32:49Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.202051
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg.ACdy-O7b-QmACgtoNQX0uZ,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg,@ΒασιληςΑνδριοπουλος-ρ1δ,@FindingGinaMarie Thank you!,2024-12-31T01:47:36Z,2024-12-31T01:47:36Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.202071
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg.ACdy-O7b-QmACguHYGG9kb,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,@ΒασιληςΑνδριοπουλος-ρ1δ Happy to help! —Judy,2024-12-31T01:51:43Z,2024-12-31T01:51:43Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.202078
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg.ACdy-O7b-QmAEChAe5bMFF,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg,@tkozikow,@FindingGinaMarie the tour description shows three hours...was that enough time to make you comfortable exploring more on your own? Our riad has recommended a local guide for a longer day (maybe 5-6 hours) which is $80 and sounds a bit pricey. Was the Airbnb tour just you and Kevin?,2025-02-06T16:03:31Z,2025-02-06T16:03:31Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.202084
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg.ACdy-O7b-QmAEDoYAPtBTt,UgwenC8KdOftSAenlC94AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Hi @tkozikow I guess it depends what you're looking for. We were able to navigate the medina fairly well even without a guide, so spending that much time would be worthwhile if you want souvenirs or else want to have a guide direct you to some of the various vendors who show off their handcrafts. Our guide took us through the medina, but it was after showing us around some other things as well (e.g., Bahia Palace, the Koutoubia Tower, Jamaa El Fanah Square, and a few other points of interest). That tour cost us $51 for two people, so I can't imagine what you're getting for $80 for one person, except that the guide is tipping the handcraft vendors for showing you their trades. —Judy",2025-02-07T02:27:08Z,2025-02-07T02:27:08Z,1,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.202089
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugzjv-F52K8GObgIItl4AaABAg.ACbrVdt9aEgACbsaj9O49b,Ugzjv-F52K8GObgIItl4AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Thank you so much for watching! We booked this tour from Airbnb experiences. I’ll link it below. Our guide was a little bit corny, but he had a great attitude and knew a good amount of information. I enjoyed stop for mint tea and a pastry. Not sure if a Sahara desert tour is on your itinerary, but we enjoyed it so much. We’d love to know what you think of Marrakesh when you come back. -Judy
📝 Colourful Tour of Marrakech: https://www.airbnb.com/experiences/604421
🎥 Morocco Travel Series: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLNT98lWfwdF0_pL4S2LnqlBz2KBX9XMCc",2024-12-29T03:00:48Z,2024-12-29T03:00:48Z,2,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.359498
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugydnbr0eYUf94B4rvB4AaABAg.ACMtyMgMwl8ACMvyX4Zs8S,Ugydnbr0eYUf94B4rvB4AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Hi @rosier3188, I want to be clear that I understand your question. I did book tours when I was in Morocco (but we are full-time travelers and that's the only time that worked for us—BUT we were there 40 days and weren't in a time crunch). We recommend ONLY ever booking your excursions online for the best experience. If you wait until you show up in Morocco and go to one of the vendors shops, you might be able to get a discount, BUT you will have a much lesser experience. We talk about it in our Sahara Desert video, and although the point we make is specifically for that type of excursion, it really applies to any type of excursion. On the street, they don't care what kind of experience you give them because there's a higher likelihood that (1) you won't leave a review; (2) people who book from those vendors don't typically even look at reviews; (3) they know that they are appealing to broad masses, so the entire experience tends to be more plain than what you book in advance. That's also because the vendors know that their reputation is on the line, which isn't necessarily the case for street vendors with shops. Note that it's illegal for them to work out the details with you on the street, so they need to hustle you into their kiosk to sort out the details.

If you are referring to our Sahara Desert tour, we would suggest you book it early online and talk with the vendor in advance so that you get exactly what you want. Here is our full series, which includes tons of details about our Sahara Desert tour and the vendor we used (not affiliated in any way and make no money from recommending them). If you need me to explain it better, please let me know! —Judy
🎥 Morocco Travel Series: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLNT98lWfwdF0_pL4S2LnqlBz2KBX9XMCc",2024-12-22T22:22:25Z,2024-12-22T22:22:25Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.542853
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwOLxhuPV6yX-UFumt4AaABAg.ACIeXOsJh7jACJD-XTUD-j,UgwOLxhuPV6yX-UFumt4AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Hi @jmw-qt2ih, Thank you so much for watching! We are glad to hear that our Japan videos were helpful. We had such a fun time there! And yes, all three of those destinations were really great times for us. We hope you will include a Sahara Desert tour (and be sure to follow all our tips for a great trip). Albania (Tirana) doesn't have the most beautiful architecture we've seen, but for the prices, walkability, family atmosphere, cafes, and good food, it totally delivers! Let us know if you have any questions about these destinations. And of course, we so appreciate that you would come back and leave such a thoughtful comment for us! We appreciate it! —Judy",2024-12-21T11:43:01Z,2024-12-21T11:43:01Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.705822
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwOLxhuPV6yX-UFumt4AaABAg.ACIeXOsJh7jACMpVny6Xys,UgwOLxhuPV6yX-UFumt4AaABAg,@jmw-qt2ih,"@FindingGinaMarie Hi Judy its Jimmy again.
I was looking at what you mentioned about the Sahara Desert  tour and it looks amazing  and an absolute must do 
My first question is about the food because while I can eat anything my wife  is very fussy,  also while we are both still mobile  I am 70 and Steph is 67  would that present any problems.",2024-12-22T21:25:56Z,2024-12-22T21:25:56Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.705840
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,UgwOLxhuPV6yX-UFumt4AaABAg.ACIeXOsJh7jACMv4EJb7IW,UgwOLxhuPV6yX-UFumt4AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Hi again, @jmw-qt2ih! The food on the Sahara Desert tour will be the same food you get everywhere else in Morocco. Tagine will be everywhere and so will couscous. Couscous is its own meal served vegetarian with vegetables (large pieces of a few assorted vegetables like carrot, butternut squash, potato and chickpeas) or also including a choice of chicken, beef, or lamb. Tagine is basically meat with a few vegetables on top (butternut squash, carrots, and preserved lemons), which also can be vegetarian. Kevin ate a lot of kefta, which is basically beef meatballs in a tomato sauce. On the tour we also got a tomato/cucumber salad in most places. They often also had fruit as dessert, and bread was always served at meals. Our videos from Morocco show a fairly good representation of the food we ate throughout the 41 days we were in Morocco. Breakfasts would typically include yogurt, fresh fruit juice, tea, and sometimes pastries. 

Just to be a little clearer, we ate a breakfast the first day just as we were starting off at a coffee shop/grocery store for tourists and lunch was also at a local restaurant (the cost was not included in the excursion price). Dinner and breakfast the second morning was at our accommodations and included soup and was a bit fancier. Day 2 lunch was at a local restaurant (again you ordered off the menu and the cost was not included in the tour). Dinner was served family style in our desert accommodations and was very nice (chicken tagine with soup and fruit for dessert and bread). Breakfast at our desert accommodations included pastries, bread, yogurt. Lunch was at a restaurant and we again chose from a menu. 

Let me know if you have any other questions. —Judy",2024-12-22T22:14:36Z,2024-12-22T22:14:36Z,0,True,,2026-05-12T02:02:15.705847
